{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"920d7b2b-01d0-477f-98c6-b2bfef77d1b1","content":"This is a **TUnit** project running on Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` for filtering, not the VSTest `--filter` syntax.\n\nThe command:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\n- `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP args\n- The treenode path is `Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test` — wildcards (`*`) match any segment\n- `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches all tests in the `SmsNotificationTests` class regardless of assembly or namespace\n\nThis will run `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dca6c572-9be8-4746-96ff-8aa92d9e313b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, the class filter uses `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. The way to run tests depends on whether it's using VSTest or MTP.\n\nLooking at the csproj, TUnit 0.6.120 - TUnit is built on MTP natively. \n\nSince TUnit projects are built as executables rather than class libraries, there's no VSTest adapter involved. With MTP, I can use `--treenode-filter` to filter by class name, following the pattern `/*/*/ClassName` or `/*/*/ClassName/MethodName`. Though `dotnet test` might support `--filter` syntax with MTP projects, TUnit specifically expects `--treenode-filter` for filtering. I should invoke the TUnit testing skill to get the exact syntax for running these filtered tests.","outputTokens":753,"requestId":"5C23:31910B:1AE937:21D4BD:69F552CB"},"id":"4a046014-b564-4b4c-9f26-6c41ac1a0272","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:26:51.814Z","parentId":"d97dff84-1